    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Wireframing</h2>
        <p>With the approval of the user flow, I then moved on wireframing the experience. Each section of the flow had their own interactions and various states to consider. In order to best contextualize and demonstrate the UX flow, I’ll break down the screens by the following steps to make it a bit more digestible:
            <ul>
                <li>Overview / Landing Page</li>
                <li>Selecting a template or segment</li>
                <li>Editing</li>
                <li>Previewing</li>
                <li>Testing</li>
                <li>Scheduling</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p><strong>***Note:</strong> Before we begin the deep dive, pre-defined campaigns, template, and segment creation are only to be handled by the GSM internal team. These assets will then be passed down to the various dealership tiers. Dealership level users will not be able to create their own templates or segments. They will only be able to make small adjustments when creating their own campaign.</p>
        <h3>Overview Page</h3> 
        <p>The main goal of the overview page was to provide Bob with both high level information about past and current campaigns, as well as, actionable elements. Playing into the narrative that Bob is not a marketer, I wanted to accentuate goals he may have and allow him to take immediate action.</p>
        <p>I achieved this by dedicating the top block element to showcase pre-selected campaigns. Pre-defined campaign cards would include information such as <strong>template preview</strong>, <strong>total recipients</strong>, <strong>channel (email / direct mail) breakdown</strong>, etc. This allows Bob to explore campaigns that were created by the GSM internal team and take immediate action. He will be able to schedule a campaign with minimal effort, improving his efficiency and allowing to focus on his service center.</p>
    </div>
    
